      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver must demonstrate correct implementation of governing equations through benchmark test cases at MRL 2 level.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent code verification was confirmed via published NASA benchmark cases for incompressible turbulent flow (lid-driven cavity, backward-facing step). Results matched reference solutions within expected discretization error bounds, confirming correct implementation of the incompressible Navier-Stokes equations and k-omega SST turbulence model used in this study."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence must be demonstrated with GCI below 5% on the quantity of interest for the production mesh.",
      "rationale": "A three-mesh GCI study was conducted per Celik et al. (2008). The production mesh (5.8M cells) achieved GCI of 2.1% for NIH and 1.8% for volume-averaged scalar stress. Iterative convergence was confirmed with all residuals below 1e-5. These results satisfy the MRL 2 discretization error requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation must be documented with sufficient fidelity to reproduce boundary conditions in the CFD model.",
      "rationale": "FDA experimental conditions were reproduced in the CFD boundary conditions: inlet flow rates (3–6 L/min), rotational speeds (2000–3500 RPM), fluid properties (bovine blood at 37°C, viscosity 3.5 mPa·s), and outlet pressure boundary conditions. Temperature and hematocrit were matched within ±2% of reported experimental values."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted NIH values must agree with experimental measurements within 15% mean absolute relative error across all validation operating points.",
      "rationale": "CFD-predicted NIH values were compared against FDA experimental data at five operating points. Mean absolute relative error was 8.3%, well within the 15% acceptance criterion. Individual point errors ranged from 3.1% to 13.7%. The rank-ordering of hemolysis severity across operating conditions was correctly predicted in all cases."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The quantities of interest (NIH, RH) must be directly relevant to the clinical decision regarding hemolysis risk in CPB applications.",
      "rationale": "The normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) and relative hemolysis index (RH) are the standard metrics used in FDA guidance for evaluating pump-induced hemolysis in blood-contacting devices. These quantities directly inform the regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1) and are the primary outputs used in the device submission decision."
    },
    {
